<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Traditional healer Derrick Shangase (52) from H section in Umlazi, south of Durban, said the course opened his eyes to the different methods used to heal people.“I have been practising traditional medicine for the past 30 years and my focus was on healing people through muthi. “But now I have learnt how important it is to give a patient your time as well. “That is the only way to get to the bottom of their problems,” said Shangase.He said he hoped similar courses would be offered to equip traditional healers with the knowledge they needed to serve their clients to the best of their ability.While some people think traditional healing is outdated, University of KwaZulu-Natal Professor Sihawukele Ngubane said healers possess a special gift that needs to be preserved.He told the traditional healers: “We value you. “What you have is a great gift from above. “We appreciate what you are doing and request that you come to the front lines of the fight against social ills. “Please do something about the killings we read about in the newspaper every day. “Ask for help from your ancestors. Make sure modern life does not overshadow our culture.”Councillor Zama Sokhasibe, who spoke on behalf of eThekwini mayor Zandile Gumede, said: “We support the initiative. “We want those who were given certificates today to know they are appreciated by the City for the work they do.”